[Student "S"]
{Partner's 2\D bid is a transfer; you respond 2\H. Partner now bids 3NT.   

Partner's 2\D bid is a transfer; you respond 2\H. Partner now bids 3NT.   

Partner tells you that he has enough points to be in game, and that he holds exactly 5 \Hs. With your 3 \Hs you know of an 8-card Major fit so you correct the contract to 4\H.

North plays 4\H. East leads the \CJ. You win the opening lead with your \CQ.

Loser List: \S = 0 : \H = ? : \D = 2 : \C = 0 :: Total = ?

The 2 \D losers are unavoidable, and even you will have to give up a trick to the Ace of trumps. So you have to make sure not to lose a second \H. 

Win the \CQ and play a small \H to dummy's \HJ, which holds the trick. 

I hope you didn't continue drawing trumps by playing the \HK. If you did then you are going down in an ice-cold contract.

The way to lose only one \H trick is to keep leading toward dummy's honors. So come to your hand with a black card and play another \H in that direction, leading through East's \HA. When you win that trick repeat the maneuver.

It is really against the odds for East to hold \H A 10 9 x. In fact it would only occur perhaps one time in seven.

But there is no reason to go down once every seven times when you don't need to.}
[Play "W"]CJ

